{"department_text": "PCs & Laptops", "level": 1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "text": "PCs & Laptops", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "description_title": "PC & Laptops", "keyword_count": {"laptops": 2, "pc": 3}, "description_wc": 195, "description_text": "Need a new notebook PC or a super portable netbook ? How about an Intel-powered Ultrabook ? If you're interested in a new tablet, such as the Asus Transformer Pad Infinity TF700 , or accessories for any of the above, Newegg is the place to look. We carry portable computers from top tier manufacturers, including HP laptops, Acer laptops, Lenovo ThinkPads, and ASUS netbooks. Every manner of laptop accessory is also available, including laptop batteries , AC adapters, laptop/notebook cases , add-on cards, docking stations , laptop memory , and solid state disks . If you're more interested in power and affordability than portability, a desktop computer might be right up your alley. Newegg stocks pre-built ready-to-use desktop PCs from popular manufacturers like HP (Hewlett-Packard), Acer, Gateway, and ASUS. Whether you're looking for a touchscreen PC, a bleeding-edge supercomputer or a capable family friendly computer on a budget, Newegg has what you're looking for! WARNING: The products listed on this page and in this category may contain chemicals known to the State of California to cause cancer, or birth defects or other reproductive harm.", "keyword_density": {"laptops": "1.1", "pc": "1.6"}, "department_id": 3},
{"department_text": "Ultrabooks & Tablets", "level": 1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Ultrabooks-Tablets/Store/ID-125", "text": "Ultrabooks & Tablets", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Ultrabooks-Tablets/Store/ID-125", "description_title": "Exploring the Intel-Powered Ultrabook", "keyword_count": {"ultrabook": 21, "intel": 3, "powered": 2}, "description_wc": 530, "description_text": "Give your old, bulky laptop the boot \u2014 the Ultrabook is here. If 2011 was the year of the tablet , then 2012 will surely go down as the year of the Ultrabook. Most people aren't yet aware of these remarkable additions to the PC market, but most will come to know just how versatile, powerful and convenient Ultrabooks can be. Some of the best Ultrabooks are already being produced by companies such as Asus, HP, Lenovo, Toshiba, Acer and Samsung. To find the Ultrabook that's right for you, check out our Ultrabook Buying Guide . What is an Ultrabook? The Ultrabook concept, spearheaded by Intel, is essentially the next step in the evolution of netbooks. A netbook is a small, lightweight laptop that has been created with portability in mind. It has no optical drive (for CDs and DVDs) yet features a battery designed to last a long time, so most of its functions are limited to what can be accomplished on the internet. This kind of product is ideal for commuters, travelers and telecommuters who don't need a ton of software or peripheral devices to get work done. An Ultrabook improves upon the netbook by giving users a more complete computing experience. These slim pieces of machinery also come packed with high-powered features, so you don\u2019t have to sacrifice performance for portability and style. Ultrabook Features To actually qualify as an Ultrabook, a PC must meet certain Intel quality standards for speed and processing power. The first generation of Ultrabooks run on Intel\u2019s second generation processors in the Core i3, i5 or i7, depending on what model you choose. And because they use a special low-wattage version of the processors, the new Ultrabooks have a much longer battery life \u2014 a five hour minimum. Ultrabooks vs. Netbooks Ultrabooks take much of the technology of existing laptop PCs and netbooks and improve them in basic ways. In addition to being lightweight like its netbook predecessor, an Ultrabook must be thin. Most weigh less than three pounds and are under an inch thick when closed. Also, the high-definition resolution of an Ultrabook is superior to most monitors available today. However, the biggest difference between an Ultrabook and a netbook is the type of hard drive each one uses. A netbook, despite lacking an optical drive, still has a relatively old-fashioned hard drive disk (HDD). This involves moving parts and requires a fan to cool so it doesn't overheat. Conversely, Ultrabooks feature solid state drive (SSD) technology, which means there are no moving parts inside of it. This is the same type of processing many smartphones and tablets use and makes booting up the Ultrabook a breeze. By using an SSD that has the operating system loaded onto it already, you\u2019ll be powered up and ready to start working within seconds. So instead of hauling around that heavy laptop through airport security and multiple business meetings, why not take a lighter approach? The Ultrabook has the power and battery life needed to carry you through a busy day without weighing you down \u2014 the perfect accessory for your modern, fast-paced lifestyle.", "keyword_density": {"ultrabook": "4.0", "intel": "0.6", "powered": "0.4"}, "department_id": 2},
