{"department_text": "PCs & Laptops", "level": 0, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Desktop-PCs/Category/ID-228", "text": "Desktop PCs", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "description_title": "Desktop PCs", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "keyword_count": {"desktop pcs": 8, "desktop": 21, "pcs": 9}, "description_wc": 638, "description_text": "Use this link for more on Desktop PCs in our Learning Center Looking for a powerful, ready-to-use computer for the home or office? A desktop PC here refers to a completely pre-built desktop computer, which is the antithesis of the self-built or DIY (do it yourself) desktop computer system. Desktop PCs are offered by brandname manufacturers, like ASUS, DELL, Hewlett-Packard, Compaq, Acer, Lenovo, Gateway and Sony VAIO or SIs (Systems Integrators) and are typically offered with full system warranties. Pre-built computers represent great choices for users that require convenience, performance and ease-of-use. Computer hardware knowledge is not a necessity. Brandname desktop PCs are capable of delivering all the functions and performance you need for your applications, including web browsing, enjoying picture and movie files and office work, as well as multimedia processing and professional 3D work. In addition, desktop PCs still allow for extensive upgrades to be performed, allowing you to make the most out of your investment. .SEOContent_TableAlignment td {vertical-align: top;} #bcaShopWindowSEO a { color: blue; text-decoration: underline; } #bcaShopWindowSEO a:active { color: red; } #bcaShopWindowSEO a:visited { color: purple; } #bcaShopWindowSEO a:hover { border: none; } .seo { color: #202020; line-height: 125%; font-family: calibri, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt;}.seo h2 { font-weight: bold; color: #043566; font-size: 14pt !important; margin-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 0px;}.seo h3 { font-weight: bold; color: #043566; font-size: 11pt !important; margin-bottom: 5px;}.seo p { margin-top: 0px; }/** Box Sizing **/.column_left { width: 47%; padding-right: 3%; float: left; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px; }.column_right { width: 47%; padding-left: 3%; float: right; margin-top: 15px; margin-bottom: 15px; } Traditionally, a desktop PC meant a large tower coupled with a monitor. Desktop PCs now have towers that range from full-size to compact, with some no more than a foot tall. There are even all-in-one PCs that eliminate the tower by combining the monitor and tower into one compact unit, which can free up some space in a crowded office. A Desktop PC that will be used for general office administration and word processing will not need huge amounts of processing power, and an octa-core processor is usually not required. Find a workable balance where the processor is powerful enough for the tasks you intend to use it for. Solid state drives are very popular, but not all Desktop PCs will need the increased read and access times that they provide. Consider getting solid state drives for desktop PC that require fast read and write speeds for specialized jobs or fast boot speeds. Otherwise, a traditional hard drive will be sufficient for most tasks. Most desktop PCs used for general administrative tasks and word processing will not require dedicated graphics cards, so you can reduce costs by purchasing desktop PCs with onboard video. However, an exception may be made for business-grade graphics cards if your organization is purchasing a desktop PC for design, simulation, rendering, or any other graphics related tasks. Also, if the tasks that the desktop PC will be performing require a lot of screen space, consider getting a desktop PC with a capable of outputting video to multiple displays to improve productivity and efficiency. Many basic desktop pc come with DVD writers, which should be sufficient for general use, but you can always add a Blu-ray drive if it is required for the tasks that the desktop PC will be doing. Keep those key points in mind when shopping for a desktop PC and you will find one that fulfills its role and fits your organization\u2019s budget. Avoid over-spending by buying one with specifications that are above and beyond what is needed. The ideal desktop PC should be sufficient for its function without being unnecessarily expensive and laden with necessary features.", "parent_text": "PCs & Laptops", "keyword_density": {"desktop pcs": "2.5", "pcs": "1.4", "desktop": "3.3"}, "department_id": 3},
{"department_text": "PCs & Laptops", "nr_products": 101, "level": -1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Mac-Hard-Drives/SubCategory/ID-552", "text": "Mac Hard Drives", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "description_title": "External Hard Drives for Macs", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/External-Hard-Drives/Category/ID-344?name=External-Hard-Drives", "keyword_count": {"external hard": 2, "hard": 6, "drives": 2, "external": 3}, "description_wc": 313, "description_text": "Mac users need to sync an external hard drive with their computer to use Time Machine, Apple's built-in file backup system. Shoppers can find and choose the right Mac hard drive by thinking about storage and portability needs. To figure out what size hard drive you should buy, think about how much computing you do each day and how many files you save. If you're a heavy user, consider buying a drive with terabytes (TB) of available storage. You'll be able to save an entire system to a device with that much room, so if you need a new computer, you will be able to reinstall everything as it was previously. These units are beneficial to people who work in creative industries and have libraries that are too expansive for a single Mac external hard drive. For example, a photographer who has hundreds of thousands of pictures saved on his or her desktop won't be able to back everything up with a smaller unit. Casual consumers should consider drives with a few hundred gigabytes (GB) of space. Buying a device with TBs of data storage would result in a great deal of wasted space for users who only have a couple thousand files that need to be saved. If you plan on bringing your external Mac hard drive everywhere you go, you'll want to purchase a unit that is light and damage-resistant. Some drives are smaller than most tablets, while other devices are large enough to be confused with video game consoles. If you're prone to damaging your gadgets, consider a drive with pads and shock protectors to defend against significant bumps and bruises. Time Machine is a convenient program to help ensure that every file is saved, and buying the right Mac hard drive can help Mac users make the most of the program.", "parent_text": "External Hard Drives", "keyword_density": {"external hard": "1.3", "hard": "1.9", "drives": "0.6", "external": "1.0"}, "department_id": 3},
