{"department_text": "PCs & Laptops", "nr_products": 672, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Headsets-Accessories/SubCategory/ID-707", "text": "Headsets & Accessories", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "description_title": "Headsets", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Input-Devices/Category/ID-29", "keyword_count": {"headsets": 4}, "description_wc": 287, "description_text": "Gamers see their hobby as serious business, so having the right tools to maximize playtime is essential. Nobody wants to mess around with desk microphones with unnecessary feedback or large computer speakers that garble in-game music and distort what other players are saying. Serious gaming requires serious headsets, and finding one that works best for you is what raises your in-game performance. Like standard pairs of headphones , headsets have a variety of styles and sizes. Some have bands that go over the top of the head, others wrap behind and still others do away with bands altogether and clip to ears to avoid stressing the temples. A wireless set may be more up a gamer's alley, as these relieve the exasperation a tethered headset can provide. The real added benefit of a headset comes from the onboard microphone, a feature that not all headsets provide but one that's worth looking for. This function gives you the ability to talk and listen without getting excessive feedback from keyboard or electronic activity, as well as reducing the amount of interference on your end so that other people in your conversation can hear you more easily. As any gamer knows, a successful raid relies partly on good communication, so it's essential that everyone in the party knows who you're dotting before someone kites the group. Headsets come in a variety of colors and styles, and picking the right one with the best additional features will depend on your preferences. Noise reducing, wireless or wired, with a slew of different wearing options and the ability to talk more easily while hammering on your keyboard, a headset is an integral part of successful online communication.", "parent_text": "Input Devices", "keyword_density": {"headsets": "1.4"}, "department_id": 3},
{"department_text": "PCs & Laptops", "nr_products": 998, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Hubs/SubCategory/ID-26", "text": "Hubs", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/PCs-Laptops/Store", "description_title": "USB Hubs", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Input-Devices/Category/ID-29", "keyword_count": {"hubs": 1, "usb": 7}, "description_wc": 318, "description_text": "Some users do not have enough USB ports on their computers to support all of their peripheral devices. If a consumer wants to connect multiple accessories, they might have to choose between which ones have the most relevant functionality and which are expendable for the time being. This is an inconvenience for those who need their devices to work efficiently and accommodate all needs. If you have too many accessories and not enough docks, a USB hub will provide the additional support you need. A hub uses one USB port on the computer itself but provides multiple ports that link with other devices - much the way a power strip creates additional electrical outlets by working from one. After purchasing a network hub, every peripheral device can stay connected to a laptop. You can connect an external hard drive, DVD burner, printer and smartphone to a computer via a single USB connection and still have extra space for more accessories. Users can leave all their peripherals attached to the hub for more convenient connection and detachment. Instead of unplugging multiple items, consumers only have to remove a USB hub's plug. This is perfect for those who need their computers to travel, such as college students who bring their notebooks to class or workers who need their laptops in the office. There are different styles of plugs to meet the needs of every shopper. Some ports are large and have over 10 USB slots so they might be best utilized in a stationary environment, while others only feature a couple of access points for more mobile use. Other network hubs are just a series of wires so consumers don't have to carry a bulky device. Peripheral accessories help users enjoy their laptops' best features. A USB hub can provide the additional support necessary so that no one ever has to choose which device to use with which program.", "parent_text": "Input Devices", "keyword_density": {"hubs": "0.3", "usb": "2.2"}, "department_id": 3},
