{"department_text": "Electronics", "nr_products": 1194, "level": -1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Camera-Tripods/SubCategory/ID-392", "text": "Camera Tripods", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Electronics/Store", "description_title": "Camera Tripods & Stands", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Digital-Cameras/Category/ID-354", "keyword_count": {"camera": 7, "tripods": 1}, "description_wc": 301, "description_text": "Photographers want to capture the perfect image every time they pick up a camera. Every picture should be clear and focused, but this may be difficult to do consistently if the camera is held in hand. Instead of thinking only about a photo's subject, photographers must make sure their hands are steady and have the correct angle for the shot. A camera tripod reduces those concerns, so these artists only have to think about what pictures to take. A tripod is a steady base for a camera that holds the device in a mounted, fixed position. Even the slightest movement on the photographer's part can cause an image to be blurry or out of focus. A camera stand eliminates the need for reshoots by eliminating much of the risk of human error. There are different tripods available depending on the chosen medium. Photographers mostly deal with still images, so it might be best to buy a stand with a static camera base to focus on one subject during a shot. For videographers who need to follow action while recording, a tripod with an adjustable head allows for easier panning. You should make sure all your equipment is safe during transport and easy to carry, as well. A bag can protect your new stand and some of your other equipment. Some carrying cases include extra padding and rigid outer shells to protect your camera from any accidents - like falling onto concrete or landing in water. Other bags are designed with a tripod in mind, so you can sling it over your shoulder and still have your hands free to take pictures while on the go. Whether you're a professional photographer or a hobbyist, it's important to make sure you're capturing an image as the eye sees it.", "parent_text": "Digital Cameras", "keyword_density": {"camera": "2.3", "tripods": "0.3"}, "department_id": 4},
{"department_text": "Electronics", "nr_products": 2208, "level": -1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Camera-Lenses/SubCategory/ID-388", "text": "Camera Lenses", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Electronics/Store", "description_title": "Camera Lenses", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Digital-Cameras/Category/ID-354", "keyword_count": {"camera": 5, "lenses": 6, "camera lenses": 2}, "description_wc": 287, "description_text": "Traditionally, only single-lens reflex (SLR) cameras or their digital (DSLR) counterparts could make use of high-powered camera lenses. However, with Micro Four technology rolling out, allowing more camera owners to take advantage of diverse accessories, it\u2019s important to understand what options are available. Individual lenses can improve your close-ups, wide shots and panoramas. Specialty camera lenses give you better image quality at night, with high-speed targets or in bright spaces with lots of refracted light sources, like beaches or snowy fields. Focal length will also determine how much of a zoom your shots will require, because it forces a perspective change past a certain point. Telephoto lenses with enhanced zoom can help get around that problem when centering on an individual subject of interest, but for those looking for a wider shot, perhaps lens diameter, rather than reach, is what's most important. A prime lens or zoom lens will be your first consideration. Prime lenses are less expensive and better for low-light situations and faster subjects, as well as being generally lighter and smaller to carry. A zoom lens will help you get close to the action no matter how far away you are, without struggling to change lenses. Deciding whether you want to focus your camera work on outdoor or indoor subjects, close-up or wide-angle events and the kind of lighting you're most likely to encounter are key for picking the right lens for you.. Remember that you can only get so much out of an individual lens. While the images you get may still look good, having the right tool for the job is crucial when you're trying to get the best image possible.", "parent_text": "Digital Cameras", "keyword_density": {"camera": "1.7", "camera lenses": "1.4", "lenses": "2.1"}, "department_id": 4},
