{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "nr_products": 780, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wireless-AP/SubCategory/ID-335", "text": "Wireless AP", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "Wireless Access Point", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wireless-Networking/Category/ID-41", "keyword_count": {"wireless": 7, "access point": 5, "wireless access point": 2}, "description_wc": 305, "description_text": "Many residences and offices were not designed with wireless networking in mind. If a space is too large or has too many barriers, an internet signal can fail to reach far-flung devices. A network degrades as it travels over the air, so a wall can prevent a computer from connecting to a router. Setting up a wireless access point creates a new source for a wireless signal, so that every Wi-Fi enabled gadget can go online successfully. The device acts as a bridge for the internet connection so it can cover a larger area without losing strength. An access point syncs with a wireless router to rebroadcast the signal it receives. Unlike a PC, which needs to be near a modem for a fast internet connection, a wireless bridge has a direct connection to the Wi-Fi router so it can be far enough away to increase the coverage area. Some devices cannot support local gadgets and require an additional ethernet port to allow wireless devices to go online. These models are usually smaller so you aren't losing much additional space because of the second unit. For offices and workspaces, there are access points that can be mounted to the wall or ceiling and don't have to sit on an employee's desk. The network coverage area will be larger as well, because the bridge is close enough to a barrier to prevent it from blocking the signal. Residential users must to consider what type of access point meets their needs. If there aren't additional ethernet jacks in rooms that don't have internet connections, consumers should make sure they buy a bridge that can support devices without an additional port. Wireless access points are a cost-effective alternative to contacting an internet service provider for increased Wi-Fi connectivity.", "parent_text": "Wireless Networking", "keyword_density": {"wireless": "2.3", "access point": "3.3", "wireless access point": "2.0"}, "department_id": 1},
{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "nr_products": 66, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Network-Bluetooth/SubCategory/ID-295", "text": "Network - Bluetooth", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "Bluetooth Adapters", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wireless-Networking/Category/ID-41", "keyword_count": {"adapters": 4, "bluetooth adapters": 2, "bluetooth": 8}, "description_wc": 306, "description_text": "There's nothing better than having a single device that can - control and connect with - an entire suite of other tools. It adds flow to your daily routine and makes it simpler to use technology when every facet works together seamlessly. Bluetooth devices are inherently capable of providing this level of connectivity, but for electronics that don't have this technology built-in, Bluetooth adapters can grant them that access. Smartphones, tablets, headsets and a multitude of other objects are, for the most part Bluetooth-ready and come with these wireless connection tools already installed. Others include GPS units, watches, media remote controls and printer/fax machine devices. Keyboards and mice are also often Bluetooth-capable tools, and all of them can network with one another through a series of interfaces to increase your user experience. A Bluetooth adapter can plug into any of these devices as well, should it come without the capability already installed. This is particularly the case for MP3 and other music devices, which can then interface with media remotes and other playback equipment. Speakers also can take these adapters, boosting your range of control. USB adapters are particularly useful when connecting with computers, and wireless connections can even replace existing wired USB cables for some peripherals. These Bluetooth dongles can be installed quickly and easily on any computer with an available port, featuring automated plug-and-play accessibility that lets you get devices connected much faster. With the move away from CD drives on newer computers and laptops, this will soon be the best and only way to gain Bluetooth connectivity with certain external hardware. Un-cluttering your workspace and streamlining your entertainment experience has never been easier with Bluetooth adapters. Get rid of the cables, reach devices from across the room, and boost your signal strength with these versatile tools.", "parent_text": "Wireless Networking", "keyword_density": {"bluetooth adapters": "1.3", "adapters": "1.3", "bluetooth": "2.6"}, "department_id": 1},
{"nr_products": 140, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Switch-Modules/SubCategory/ID-570", "text": "Switch Modules", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_wc": 0, "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wired-Networking/Category/ID-40", "parent_text": "Wired Networking", "department_text": "Computer Hardware", "department_id": 1},
{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "nr_products": 690, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wireless-Routers/SubCategory/ID-145", "text": "Wireless Routers", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "Wireless Network Routers", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wireless-Networking/Category/ID-41", "keyword_count": {"wireless network routers": 2, "routers": 6, "wireless": 8, "network": 15, "wireless network": 5}, "description_wc": 297, "description_text": "Use this link for more information on Wireless Routers in our Learning Center Home wireless routers allow you to connect your home computers together into a network. If you want to use your router as a firewall also, make sure you purchase one that has a built-in firewall. Otherwise, you can purchase a firewall separately. Wireless network routers will allow you to connect computers, notebook computers, PDAs and printers without wires. They are also useful for connecting laptops to the Internet and other networks, such as at work or at home. If you want to use a wireless network router, you need to have a wireless network adapter installed in any computer that you connect to your network. If these are not already in the computers, you'll need to purchase them and add them in. To network your home computers to each other, you can use an access point instead, but we recommend routers because you can also use them for Internet sharing and firewall security. Also, home routers tend to be less expensive than access points. The Importance of Security with Wireless Network Routers Security is especially important when using a wireless network. Basically, anybody within the range of your network who has the right equipment can access it. It is very easy for them to use a network detection program to access your network. Therefore, use WEC or MAC address filtering. This is a unique hardware identifier that gives each network device its own identity. WEP, or Wireless Encryption Protocol, is another way to identify your network devices. It establishes a shared key between the access point and clients, using the key to encrypt and de-encrypt the data that is transferred between them. This is enough security for most home network uses.", "parent_text": "Wireless Networking", "keyword_density": {"wireless network routers": "2.0", "routers": "2.0", "wireless": "2.7", "network": "5.1", "wireless network": "3.4"}, "department_id": 1},
{"nr_products": 867, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Power-Distribution-Unit/SubCategory/ID-1042", "text": "Power Distribution Unit", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_wc": 0, "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Servers-Workstations/Category/ID-271", "parent_text": "Servers & Workstations", "department_text": "Computer Hardware", "department_id": 1},
{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "nr_products": 187, "level": -2, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wired-Routers/SubCategory/ID-28", "text": "Wired Routers", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "Wireless Network Routers", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Wired-Networking/Category/ID-40", "keyword_count": {"wireless network routers": 1, "routers": 3, "wireless": 8, "network": 13, "wireless network": 3}, "description_wc": 265, "description_text": "Use this link for more information on Wireless Routers in our Learning Center Home wireless routers allow you to connect multiple devices together wirelessly into a network to share resources and access the internet. Examples of some of the devices you can connect to your network include desktop computers, notebook computers, external hard drives, PDAs, stand alone or all-in-one copy / fax / printers, media players, entertainment devices and more all without wires. If you setup your network to be 100% wireless then you will need to ensure that every device that you want to add to the network has a wireless network adapter installed otherwise they will have no way to access the network. If these are not already in the computers, you'll need to purchase them and add them in. Once all devices are configured and set up you will be able to share files and resources across the network. The Importance of Security with Wireless Network Routers Security is especially important when using a wireless network. Basically, anybody within the range of your network who has the right equipment can access it if it is not secured. Therefore we recommend safety features such as WEC or MAC address filtering. This is a unique hardware identifier that gives each network device its own identity. WEP, or Wireless Encryption Protocol, is another way to identify your network devices. It establishes a shared key between the access point and clients, using the key to encrypt and de-encrypt the data that is transferred between them. This is enough security for most home network uses.", "parent_text": "Wired Networking", "keyword_density": {"wireless network routers": "1.1", "routers": "1.1", "wireless": "3.0", "network": "4.9", "wireless network": "2.3"}, "department_id": 1},
