{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "level": 0, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Cases/Category/ID-9", "text": "Computer Cases", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "Computer Cases", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "keyword_count": {"cases": 9, "computer": 10, "computer cases": 4}, "description_wc": 275, "description_text": "Computer cases are one of the most important components of a computer, since they have to house the motherboard, processor, video cards, audio cards and add-in cards, as well as your hard drives and optical drives. Most of the computer cases are made of steel or aluminum. Some parts of a computer case can also be made of plastic. Computer cases can be divided into several categories by their sizes and purpose. Mainstream computer case styles and form factors include ATX Mid Tower, ATX Full Tower, MicroATX, Mini Tower and Desktop Cases. HTPC (Home Theater PC), or Media Center Cases are used for a personal computer specifically designed to help you manage your multimedia and video assets, sometimes including digital video recorder functions. Its connections and form are arranged for easy wiring to a TV, in-home network or Home Theater System. Usually, HTPC/Media Center Cases are or can be controlled by a remote. HTPC/Media Center Cases also can be used to serve media files to other computers /devices on a network, play games or provide access to other media files and programs. Newegg is proud to offer a wide variety of computer cases, case accessories, controller panels, HTPC/Media Center Cases and server chassis. Find the computer case you are looking for at Newegg.com, and enjoy the smoothest, most pleasurable online shopping experience to be found anywhere! WARNING: Products with exposed solder may contain lead, a chemical known to the State of California to cause cancer, birth defects and other reproductive harm. Please wash hands after handling internal components and motherboards and avoid inhalation of fumes if heating the solder.", "parent_text": "Computer Hardware", "keyword_density": {"cases": "3.3", "computer": "3.6", "computer cases": "2.9"}, "department_id": 1},
