{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "nr_products": 711, "level": -1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Cases/SubCategory/ID-7", "text": "Computer Cases", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "ATX Computer Cases", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Cases/Category/ID-9", "keyword_count": {"computer cases": 2, "computer": 7, "cases": 3, "atx computer cases": 1, "atx": 4}, "description_wc": 207, "description_text": "Use this link for more on ATX Computer Cases in our Learning Center The ATX (Advanced Technology Extended) form factor was created by Intel in 1995. It was the first big change in computer case and motherboard design in a long time. ATX took over AT completely as a standard form factor for new systems. Version 2.2 of the ATX form factor was issued in 2004. The computer case or chassis encases and protects all computer components installed within it and provides a unified external appearance. It therefore plays a very significant role in the total computer system. Not only does the computer case affect the type and number of components that can be installed, its layout and design also determines the cooling performance and reliability of the entire system. The massive selection of computer cases on Newegg.com ensures that you will be able to find something made just for you, regardless of the application: normal home use, office use or power gaming/DIYing. WARNING: Products with exposed solder may contain lead, a chemical known to the State of California to cause cancer, birth defects and other reproductive harm. Please wash hands after handling internal components and motherboards and avoid inhalation of fumes if heating the solder.", "parent_text": "Computer Cases", "keyword_density": {"computer cases": "1.9", "computer": "3.4", "cases": "1.4", "atx": "1.9", "atx computer cases": "1.4"}, "department_id": 1},
{"department_text": "Computer Hardware", "nr_products": 43, "level": -1, "url": "http://www.newegg.com/HTPC-Media-Center-Cases/SubCategory/ID-690", "text": "HTPC / Media Center Cases", "department_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Hardware/Store", "description_title": "HTPC Cases", "parent_url": "http://www.newegg.com/Computer-Cases/Category/ID-9", "keyword_count": {"cases": 2, "htpc": 5}, "description_wc": 290, "description_text": "There is a great deal of equipment to buy for a home theater. Consumers want the perfect screen, audio system and media hub. Some users build their own home theater PC (HTPC), so they have equipment that meets their exact specifications. The system should be stored in a HTPC case, so it's not just a loose collection of wires and processors. Finding the best HTPC case comes down to what the system demands and the consumer's preferences. Some storage units have more ports and input bays than others, so users need to consider what their HTPC is going to be used for and what type of connections it demands. Cases also come with different types of available connections, like USB ports and audio jacks for microphones and headphones. Size should be one of your bigger concerns when choosing a media center PC case. Figure out how much space your system will need to function properly and remain secure. This allows users to avoid redesigning a PC's setup because of an excess or a lack of storage space. For shoppers who have an eye on the overall aesthetic of their home theater, different styles of cases are available. If you want a case to go unnoticed, there are basic black models that disappear into the shadows. Different colors are available if you want your HTPC case to stick out or match the color scheme in the room. There are even some modeled after retro radios, to make the system as fun as it is functional. Finding the right home theater pc case doesn't have to be difficult. Consider all of your system's needs before buying anything to ensure that your purchase is the correct one.", "parent_text": "Computer Cases", "keyword_density": {"cases": "0.7", "htpc": "1.7"}, "department_id": 1},
